% --- New paragraph after the 2x2 design-space discussion ---

The 2$\times$2 design space organizes \emph{where} coordination
data moves, but leaves a second axis silent: \emph{who} reads it.
Push designs (CA-MCP, LangGraph handoffs) hand the framework the
writer decision and let downstream readers consume what is
delivered; pull designs as in v1 of ET-MCP give the agent both
sides---the agent is the active reader, deciding when and how to
incorporate peer state.  A third combination is already a deployed
primitive in production multi-agent runtimes but has not been
studied as a coordination architecture: the framework acts as the
active reader, intercepts the agent's tool call, queries the
coordination store on the agent's behalf, and rewrites the tool
\emph{response} to carry the result.  Strands'
\texttt{BeforeToolCallEvent}/\texttt{AfterToolCallEvent}~\cite{strandshooks2025},
Amazon Bedrock AgentCore Policy~\cite{agentcorepolicy2025},
LangChain middleware's
\texttt{wrap\_tool\_call}~\cite{langchainmiddleware2026}, and
Microsoft Agent Framework's function
middleware~\cite{msagentframework2026} all expose this hook surface
today---for blocking, validation, retries, and caching, not for
coordination.  We name this design \emph{intercept} and run the
first controlled head-to-head against pull under matched payload.
The empirical result is counter to the production-stack intuition:
at $n{=}100$ tasks on $\tau^2$-bench retail, the agent-side reader
(pull) significantly outperforms the framework-side reader
(intercept) on pass$^k$ at comparable token cost
(\S\ref{sec:eval:results:retail-intercept}, Cliff's
$\delta=$$+0.18$ on pass$^1$, sign test $p=0.004$).  Selective
agent reading, not blind framework injection, carries the
architectural win.

% --- Revised C2 contribution bullet (replaces v1's C2) ---

\item \textbf{(C2) First controlled head-to-head of reader-side
    coordination architectures.}  Holding the underlying event
    store, writer policy, event taxonomy, and MCP transport
    constant, we compare two reader-side architectures:
    agent-as-reader (\emph{pull}) via a curated peer-warnings
    summary at trial start, and framework-as-reader
    (\emph{intercept}) via a \texttt{[PEER-WARNING]} block prepended
    to a tool's response when the call's (name, arguments) match a
    peer event of a prior failed trial of the same task.  On
    $\tau^2$-bench retail~\cite{tau2bench2025} at $n{=}100$ tasks
    (600 trials, Claude Haiku~4.5), pull reaches
    pass$^1$=$0.62$ and pass$^2$=$0.44$; intercept reaches
    pass$^1$=$0.44$ and pass$^2$=$0.33$; no-coordination reaches
    pass$^1$=$0.54$ and pass$^2$=$0.38$.  Pull beats no-coordination
    by $+8$\,pp on pass$^1$ and $+6$\,pp on pass$^2$; intercept
    underperforms no-coordination by $-10$\,pp and $-5$\,pp.  Pull
    significantly dominates intercept under matched payload (27 vs.\ 9
    task-level wins on pass$^1$, sign test $p=0.004$ uncorrected,
    Cliff's $\delta=+0.18$; 18 vs.\ 7 wins on pass$^2$,
    $p=0.043$).  This is, to our knowledge, the first such
    head-to-head under matched payload---the closest prior comparison
    (Ou et al.~\cite{ou2025coordination}: notebook vs.\ orchestrator
    on TravelPlanner) does not include the framework-side
    intercept arm.  The within-system TravelPlanner ablation
    (C2$^{\prime}$, below) generalizes: agent-mediated selective
    reading is the load-bearing channel both within-system at
    matched payload and across protocols at the public-benchmark
    level.

\item \textbf{(C2$^\prime$) Within-system corroboration on TravelPlanner.}
    A nine-condition factorial on TravelPlanner (810 trials,
    Haiku~4.5) holds the trace-event payload constant and varies the
    retrieval channel and selection policy.  The load-bearing
    contrast is default-vs-push\_negative: delivering the same
    negative-knowledge payload via structured push instead of through
    \texttt{trace.query} recovers part of the redundancy gain
    ($5.2\%$ vs.\ ET-MCP default $3.9\%$, vs.\ $6.8$--$9.8\%$
    push baselines) but underperforms pull, isolating the access
    \emph{channel} as load-bearing under constant payload.  This
    isolation is what generalizes to the $\tau^2$ public-benchmark
    finding above.  A Silo-Bench sweep at $N{=}5$ (360 trials)
    corroborates the mechanism on a third public benchmark; full
    methodological details, ablations, and the MiniTrip negative
    control appear in \S\ref{sec:evaluation}.

% --- Additional contribution to add as C5 ---

\item \textbf{(C5) Anthropic-native $\tau^2$-bench measurement
    infrastructure.}  $\tau^2$-bench's bundled litellm-based
    pipeline produces malformed Anthropic-API message histories on
    multi-turn dual-control retail tasks, yielding $\geq 30\%$
    silent infra-error rates with the stock \texttt{LLMAgent} on
    Anthropic Haiku in our measurements, a failure class consistent
    with multiple open BerriAI/litellm
    issues~\cite{litellmissue12404,litellmissue15322}.  We release
    a $\sim$700-line drop-in replacement that re-uses
    $\tau^2$'s domain database, tools, task definitions, and
    DB-hash reward function but constructs its conversation state
    directly against the Anthropic Messages API.  Zero infra errors
    at 600 trials.  We expect this to be useful measurement
    infrastructure for groups evaluating Anthropic deployments on
    the $\tau$-bench family and reproducing claims that rely on
    multi-turn tool-call sequences, addressing a documented
    reproducibility gap that bears directly on the workshop theme
    of post-deployment trust controls.
